english:
  title: Stupa Inscription for the Venerable Zhikong of the Western Heaven
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    According to the transmission of the Hundred and Eight Patriarchs of Kasyapa, the Venerable Zhikong—dharma name Shanxian—came from the Western regions. In the Taiding era, he met the emperor at the waters of Nanshui and discoursed on the Buddha's law with such eloquence that the ruler was pleased. The emperor commanded his ministers to provide the master annually with robes and provisions, but the master declined, saying, "I do not seek these things." He departed eastward to wander Korea, paying homage at Diamond Mountain where he established a meditation hall. When summoned back to Yanking, in the early years of the Tianli era, the emperor commanded him to lecture on the dharma within the inner palace, and the Son of Heaven himself came to listen. The other monks, emboldened by imperial favor, grew arrogant and envious, fearing the master would eclipse their status. They obstructed his teachings. Soon after, some of these monks were executed and others banished, while the master's fame spread throughout the realm. When the empress and crown prince received him in the Lianhua Pavilion and asked about the dharma, the master replied, "The Buddha's teaching has its own earnest practitioners. Your Majesty need only concentrate on governance—this is most auspicious." He added, "Ten thousand blessings, ten thousand blessings—yet if even one is lacking, one cannot be sovereign of all under heaven." When offered precious pearls and jade, he refused them entirely.

    From the Tianli era onward, for more than ten years, the master neither ate nor spoke. When he finally did speak again, he would sometimes declare, "I am the master of all under heaven," and would address the imperial concubines, saying, "You are all my attendants." Those who heard this were astonished, yet none dared inquire. When news reached the emperor, he said, "He is a king among the dharma—it is fitting that he carries himself so. What concern is this of our household?" When the armies of the Central Plain were about to rise, the master addressed a gathering, saying, "Do you know how great my forces are? In this place there are ten thousand soldiers, in that place there are ten thousand soldiers." The temple where he dwelt was inhabited entirely by Korean monks. One day he suddenly asked them, "Why do you rebel?" He moved to strike the drum for an assault but stopped. Days later, the Liaoyong provincial office reported that Korean forces had invaded the border. The capital, being a gathering place of many people, the master repeatedly urged them, "Depart quickly." Soon after, the emperor fled northward and the armies of the Central Plain entered the city, establishing a government they called Beiping. Could the master's words have been mere coincidence?

    The master himself said: "My ancestor's name was Siziaxie, my grandfather's name was Hufan—both were kings of Kapilavstu. My father's name was Man, and he was king of Magadha. My mother was a princess of Xiangzhi. My two elder brothers were Silikala and Silikamani. My parents prayed to the Great Wrathful Deity of the East, and through their devotion I was born. In my childhood, I loved purity and never consumed wine or polluting foods. At five years old, I went to study both the writings of our nation and the learning of foreign lands, grasping the great principles in outline before abandoning such studies.

    "When my father fell gravely ill and medicine proved ineffective, a diviner said, 'If the eldest son renounces the world, the king's illness will be cured.' My father asked his three sons, and I answered at once. He was greatly gladdened and called me by my childhood name, asking, 'Loudaladhuopa, can you truly do this?' My mother, because I was the youngest, was at first reluctant, yet in time she overcame her attachment and consented to let me enter the sangha. My father's illness was immediately cured.

    "At eight years old, I received the three robes and was sent to the Nalanda Monastery to study under the lecturer Lüxian. There I was tonsured and received the five precepts. As I studied the Great Perfection of Wisdom Sutra, understanding arose within me. When I inquired of the lecturer concerning the realms of all Buddhas, sentient beings, emptiness, and space, he replied, 'That which is neither existent nor non-existent—this is true wisdom. Go to the south to Mount Auspicious in the Land of Lankavata, to the teacher Puming, there to investigate the deepest meanings.' I was then nineteen years old.

    "With great determination, I traveled alone to meet my teacher at the Apex Sound Hermitage. He asked, 'From the land of Central India to this place, can you count the steps?' I could not answer. I withdrew and sat in a stone cave for six months. When understanding awakened and I tried to rise, my two legs were bound together as one. The local king summoned a physician, who gave me medicine and I was healed. I told my teacher, 'Two legs make one step.' He then entrusted me with the robes and begging bowl, placed his hand upon my head, and gave this prediction: 'Coming down the mountain in a single step, you are truly a lion's cub. Two hundred and forty-three have received the dharma from my assembly, yet few have deep karmic connections with sentient beings. You shall spread my teaching far and wide. Go forth with vigor!'

    "He named me Sunatishaya—in the Han tongue, 'One Pointing to Emptiness.' I composed a verse to express gratitude for his compassion and said to the assembly, 'In going forward, vast emptiness opens before you. In retreating, ten thousand dharmas sink together.' With one great shout, I departed.

    "When first I sought my teacher, I passed through many lands. In one region where monks were lecturing the Lotus Sutra, I composed verses resolving their doubts. In the land of Dantuo, where men and women dwelled together naked, I revealed the greater way. When I arrived at the Kingdom of Fragrant Attainment, the king, hearing of my coming, rejoiced saying, 'This is my nephew!' I did not remain. A master of the Huayan teaching was expounding the twenty forms of the bodhisattva mind. I taught him how the one contains the many and the many contain the one. On the coast of Karingga, at Tortoise Peak Mountain, Brahmin ascetics dwelt. They taught that by hurling oneself from a ten-thousand-fathom cliff in death, one attains rebirth as a king in heaven. I said, 'Practice lies in the mind—what has the body to do with it?' and taught them the six perfections and the ten stages of the bodhisattva path. During the summer retreat at Mount Marichi, I eventually reached the land of Lankavata.

    "After taking leave of my teacher and descending the mountain, an old monk who guarded the seamless stupa met me midway. Knowing that I had attained realization, he asked me to expound the dharma. I composed verses in praise of the stupa and departed. In the land of Yu, where the ruler had faith in heterodox teachings, I was summoned and subjected to trials with courtesans, yet I remained unmoved as one already dead. The king marveled and said, 'Surely this is an extraordinary person.' The heterodox masters had constructed Mount Meru from wood and stone, placing mountains upon men's heads, chests, and thighs. They made offerings of wine and food to these mountains, and men and women coupled before them, calling it 'the worship of yin and yang.' I expounded the principles of delusion and enlightenment, exposing their false doctrine. I aided the king in embracing the true Buddha-way, expressing myself through verses. The king answered in verse, and I responded in verse again. The king gifted me precious pearls and beads. A nun in the assembly asked, 'Between this master and this disciple, who is in the middle?' With one shout, the nun attained great enlightenment and composed the verse, 'An elephant king passes through the eye of a needle.'

    "In the Lion Land, I beheld the Buddha's alms bowl and the Buddha's footprint. From a single bowl of rice, ten thousand monks can be fed, and the footprint radiates light from time to time. I paid homage to both. The kingdom of Mariyala held faith in Brahminism; I did not enter there. In Charavata, where both orthodox and heterodox teachings were revered, I sat upon the seat and spoke. A nun present silently attained accord. In Karana, also devoted to heterodox paths, the king rejoiced greatly upon seeing me. I showed him the Scripture of Great Adornment, Precious Dharma King, the chapter on the King Maheshvara's past cause. The king exclaimed, 'There is a true dharma beyond dharma!' The heterodox followers sought to harm me, so I fled the city. Darkness was falling when a tiger appeared. My attendant, hearing a bird's call, climbed a tree to escape, and I said to him, 'Since you know the speech of creatures, can you understand the dharma I teach?' He was silent. I struck him thrice with the staff, and he attained awakening.

    "In the land of Shentou, where endless desert stretched before me, I found a tree with fruit like peaches. Hunger overwhelming me, I ate two and had not finished when a heavenly spirit came and established me in a vast celestial palace. An old man sat upright and said, 'Thief, why do you not bow?' I replied, 'I am a disciple of the Buddha. Why should I bow to you?' He rebuked me, saying, 'If you are a Buddhist disciple, why did you steal the fruit?' I answered, 'Hunger and thirst pressed upon me.' He said, 'To take what is not given is theft. Now I release you—guard well the precepts,' and he closed my eyes. In a moment, I found myself on the other shore. I lay upon a log to boil water, but that log was a great serpent.

    "In the land of Tiluo, a woman sought union with me. Hungry for food, I seemed about to agree, but asked her which of her horses was the finest. She told me truthfully, and I mounted it and rode swiftly, as if flying, arriving at another border. Suddenly a man seized me and made me tend his sheep. When heavy snow came, I entered a cave and sat in meditation for seven days and nights. White radiance emerged from the cave. The man swept away the snow, entered, saw me sitting in perfect lotus posture, and was greatly pleased. He offered me clothes and jewels, but I refused. Both man and woman took refuge in the dharma, and they showed me the right path.

    "After traveling long without seeing another soul, I suddenly encountered paths and rejoiced greatly. A man there seized me and brought me to the king. He knelt before the throne and said, 'Heaven is dry. Surely this is a demon. I beg you, kill him.' The king replied, 'Release him first. If no rain falls in three days, then we kill him.' I burned incense, offered a prayer, and great rains fell for three days.

    "In Chhalengta, there was a mad monk. When people came, he placed three ox heads on the ground, set a meditation cushion upon them, and sat in silence. I burned that place with a glance, and he cried out, 'The mountains, rivers, and earth have become one!' By the Anavatapta lake, Monk Daoyan dwelt in a small hut made of grass. When people approached, he set it afire, crying 'Fire! Fire!' I came, and he cried the same, so I kicked over his water vessel. He said, 'What a pity. You came too late.'

    "In Maluosa, where people revere the Buddha yet have mixed orthodox and heterodox paths, I expounded a refutation of false doctrine, and the heterodox followers turned to the right way. East of the city, a master named Baohe cleared the land around his dwelling into fields, placed a vessel of vegetable seeds, and when people came, merely tended the field without speaking. I followed him, scattering the seeds, and he cried out, 'Vegetables grow! Vegetables grow!' In the city was a weaver who did not speak when people came but continued weaving. I cut the weaving with a knife, and the weaver said, 'My weaving of many years is complete!'

    "In Anavata, Monk Shengyi dwelt in a kiln. Seeing people approach, he smeared soot on his face, danced, and withdrew. I rebuked him with a verse. In the land of Zhaosa, Monk Nada dwelt by the roadside for years, greeting arrivals with 'Welcome!' and departures with 'Farewell!' I suddenly struck him three times with my staff, and he returned one punch.

    "In the land of Tilhou, Brahminism flourished greatly. I withdrew without engaging. In Tingqili, true and false teachings flowed together. I met robbers who stripped me naked. In Negara, the king received me in his inner chambers and requested teachings. A master named Baofeng was expounding the sutras. I joined him in harmonious discourse. Traveling eastward for several days, I came upon a high mountain called the Iron Mountain, with no earth, stone, grass, or trees. Where the sun shines at dawn, its form is like fire, and it is also called Flame Mountain. It takes seven or eight days to reach the summit. There are some seventeen or eighteen kingdoms, extending horizontally to the northern heavens, numbering we know not how many thousands of li. An eastern river issues forth with high banks on both sides. A bridge crosses where ice and snow do not melt—this is called the Snow Mountain. In extreme hunger and poverty, I subsisted on wild fruits until reaching the border of the Western regions.

    "When I came to propagate the dharma in the Central Kingdom, I met the great master Mohabantuoda from North India while in the Western regions. Together we arrived in Yanking. Not long after, I ventured westward to the residence of the King of Anxi. There I met the king's preceptor, who asked me to remain and study the dharma. My intention was to wander widely, so I said to him, 'Our Buddha way takes compassion as its foundation. When you study this, does your aspiration grow even stronger?' He replied, 'Sentient beings have accumulated immeasurable evil karma since beginningless time. With a single true word, I deliver them beyond birth and death into celestial joy.' I said, 'Your words are false. The one who kills is himself killed by another. Life and death are mutual vengeance—this is the root of suffering.' He said, 'That is the heterodox way.' I replied, 'Compassion is the true Buddha way. You reverse this, so you are truly heterodox.' When the king offered gifts, I refused them.

    "In Modieya city in the Western regions, the people could be transformed. A mantra-master envied me and placed poison in my tea. Fortunately, an envoy from the capital arrived and invited me to return, intending to have me teach alongside the great master. Our doctrines did not accord, so I departed. A mantra-master in Gadan sought to kill me, so I went to Hsia city. The ruler there was overjoyed to see me, but the heterodox followers, jealous, broke one of my teeth. As I was about to leave, they lay in wait on the road determined to kill me, yet the ruler protected me and sent me on my way. I reached Shu and paid homage before the great image of Samantabhadra, sitting in meditation for three years. At the Great Poison River, I encountered bandits and again fled naked. In the Luolos region, a monk gave me robes and a woman gave me garments. I accepted these offerings from the faithful. With other monks, I received a goose that the family wished to slaughter for food. I struck the woman, she wept, and the monk grew angry and drove me out. I heard that a local official had erected a statue of me, and prayers to it for drought relief, rain, and healing from disease all received responses.

    "At the Jinsha River checkpoint, a guard saw me dressed as a woman with long hair and was puzzled, asking where I came from. I did not speak their language, so I wrote in Indian script, but they did not recognize it. I was detained there. Later, lying in a stone crevice, I suddenly found myself on the other shore without knowing how. The ferryman was amazed, bowed, and paid homage. West of Yunnan city stood a temple. I ascended the gate tower and entered meditation. The resident monks invited me into the city to the Zubian monastery. I sat beneath a parasol tree. That night rain fell, yet by morning my robes were not wet. I made a prayer for clear weather at the provincial office, and it responded immediately.

    "During summer retreat at Longquan Temple, I transcribed the Perfection of Wisdom Sutra in Sanskrit. When many gathered and water was scarce, I commanded a dragon to bring forth a spring to sustain them. In Dali, I declined all food offerings and ate only nine walnuts daily to sustain myself. The people of Jinseci, a district of the Tewo region, took me as their teacher and erected a statue in a shrine. I heard that some reckless fellows threw my statue into the mud with their staff, yet could not lift it; repenting and apologizing, they easily retrieved it as before.

    "At Anning, a monk asked about the past triumphs of Xuanzang when he entered Tang—how even in remote regions, the language was understood. By then I had learned Yunnan speech, so I replied, 'Past and present differ; the sacred and ordinary follow different paths.' When he requested teaching on the precepts, the monks burned their crowns and arms in their zeal. Both officials and common people did likewise. On the Central-Qing route, temples requested me to expound the dharma five times. The crown prince took me as his teacher and bowed before me. The Luolo people, who originally knew neither Buddha nor monks, all gave rise to faith upon my arrival, and even the flying birds seemed to chant the Buddha's name.

    "In Guizhou, officials of the regional command all received the precepts. Peoples from various caves and regions—Maoман, Yao, Qinghong, Huazhu, Daya, and Galing—all came with rare vegetables to request the precepts. At Zhenyuan there was a Temple of the Horse King Spirit. Those passing by boat had to make flesh offerings; if they did not, the boat would be damaged. With one great shout, I released the boat to proceed. Traveling the Changde route, I paid homage to the statues of the patriarchs Vajra and White Stag and to the self-sculpted image of Avalokiteshvara. Dongling Lake has many miraculous phenomena. I was able to still wind and rain. When I passed through, wind arose and waves surged. I expounded the three refuges and five precepts in alternating Sanskrit and Chinese, and the storm ceased. Previously, those who made offerings left silk shoes at night, yet by morning they were all broken. After my visit, all ceased these offerings and used only vegetable tributes. When the Provincial Councillor of Huguang tried to expel me, I said, 'I am a poor monk from the Western heaven, having come far to pay respects to the emperor and assist in propagating the true dharma. Do you not wish me to pray for the emperor's longevity?' Passing through the Eastern Grove monastery at Mount Lu, I saw my former body's stupa standing intact with bones not yet decayed.

    "When Huaxi asked the meaning of wisdom, I said, 'The three minds cannot be grasped.' The crown prince of Yangzhou sent me by boat to the capital. The wife of the Great Shun chancellor, a Korean woman named Wei, received me at the Chongrensi to administer precepts. Shortly after, I arrived in Lancheng in the Taiding era, and this is when I received imperial favor."

    Alas, the master's travels were thus—truly different from other men. From the Tianli era onward, the master put off monastic robes and took up secular dress. Madame Kim, wife of the great noble Chahantiemuer, also a Korean, became his disciple. She purchased a residence at Chengqingli, established a temple there, and invited the master to dwell within. The master named the temple 'Dharma Source,' saying that the waters of the world flow from west to east, taking this as his metaphor. The master wore his hair in braids with a white beard, his bearing dark and lustrous. His clothing and food were of great luxury. In ordinary life he was dignified and austere, and all who saw him felt reverence and fear.

    In the winter of the twenty-third year of Zhizhen, an eunuch came. The master said, 'Tell your sovereign—shall I depart after my birthday or before my birthday?' The reply came swiftly through imperial messenger Chapanitiang: the master was to remain through the winter. The master again said, 'The Tianshou temple is my hall of remembrance.' That year, on the twentieth day of the eleventh month, he passed into nirvana in the Guihua abbot's quarters—a place he himself had constructed and named. By imperial decree, the provincial, bureau, and court officials conducted the palanquin with full ceremony to the Tianshou temple. The following year, the imperial censor and chancellor Tuqiantiemuer and the prime minister Paitian came bearing incense to pay respects. Using fragrant clay and a fabric wrapping, with plum and cinnamon and ice, they molded the master's body into a statue. In autumn of the year Wushen, when armies pressed the city, the master's body was cremated and divided into four portions. Daxuan, Qinghui, Faming, and the interior official Zhang Lüji each took a portion.

    His disciple Daxuan crossed the sea and brought his portion to this land. The commandery administrator Dadudu, receiving it from Qinghui, brought it together with his portion to return to our homeland. On the sixteenth day of the ninth month in the year Renzi, by royal command, a stupa was erected at Huiyan temple. When about to entomb the relics, several fragments of sharira were discovered. The master brought from India two scrolls of the Manjushri Sutra on the Precept of Non-arising. Secretary Wei Dapu wrote a preface; the master's own hand copied the Surangama Sutra; and the imperial calligrapher Ouyang wrote a colophon.

    The master's verses were numerous, recorded separately, and widely circulated. Wu Wujian Nengneng of Yunnan took refuge with the master at age seven and went forth into monastic life. Even then he said, 'Master's age has completed one full cycle of sixty years.' Wu attained seventy-five when the master entered nirvana. The monk Jiwenjiang Renjiе testified: The master's disciple Dayun, former abbot of Linguan temple, planned to record the master's conduct. The longer the time, the more diligent the effort. The commandery administrator Dadudu, crossing difficult terrain for thousands of li, bore the master's relics as one would serve a living being, ensuring the funeral was without regret. A disciple of Laiweng said: 'Our master also once took the master as his teacher—so the master is our patriarch. Together with the master's disciple Miaocan, abbess of the Pure Karma nunnery, we purchased stone to erect a stupa at the cliff of Huiyan.' Is this not the filial piety of worthy descendants? News of this reached the throne, and imperial command was given: Minister Se shall compose the inscription; Minister Xiu shall transcribe it; Minister Zhonghe shall carve the characters.

    Minister Se said: 'The master's body, having been consumed by fire, is divided into four portions. I know not where the remaining relics rest, nor who seeks the inscription to ensure transmission, nor whose brush shall write it. Nor do I know whether Master Zhikong remains here or elsewhere, whether he has like the cicada's shell cast off his form and ceased to regard such matters, or whether his disciples, wishing to repay his grace, do this from compulsion. I cannot be unmoved by this. Receiving the imperial command with reverence and trembling, I compose this inscription:'

    *The master's traces began in the western regions—*
    *Son of King Man, true heir of Puming.*
    *At Lancheng, favorable fortune met him—*
    *Why so late the Lianhua audience?*
    *Surveying my own path's turns,*
    *What realm remained unvisited?*
    *Like water from a rooftop's edge,*
    *Like stones cast upon still water—*
    *In Tianli's favor toward monks,*
    *This master alone received supreme regard.*
    *In robes worn now, his renown grows ever higher.*
    *Wild utterances, playful words—*
    *No common person could fathom them.*
    *Speaking of war before its fire caught—*
    *Clear as black and white distinguished.*
    *The clarity of foreknowing—*
    *This is the refinement of the Way.*
    *Some doubted, some reviled,*
    *Yet his mind remained at ease.*
    *Sharira now radiates brilliance—*
    *All reverence has been aroused.*
    *Who says human nature cannot accord with the ultimate?*
    *Here at Huiyan, stone marks the dharma's watch,*
    *No falsehood shall alter it—*
    *Let this endure as eternal testimony.
